  <context>
    <background>
      Operator (2026-06-29) approved Option B and made docs a binding requirement: "ensure we have documentation of the architecture and component model because we will need it for Insights Engine (and many other areas)". Without this doc, every future consumer team rediscovers the architecture, re-debates the design, and likely diverges. With this doc, new consumers are authored in days using the established pattern.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="111" status="must-complete-first">T111 implementation provides the canonical reference code that docs describe.</dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>T113 source rewrites (lambda → flatMap, pipe → nested subexpression) provide additional concrete examples for the maker guide's "advanced expressions" section.</item>
      <item>T117 widget UAT may produce the first end-to-end "this is what it actually does" screenshot for the maker guide's reference example section.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0" name="Rigor Declaration">
      Output: 🔒 RIGOR LEVEL: STANDARD · 📋 REASON: documentation task, no source mod · Proceeding with Step 0...
    </step>
    <step order="1" name="Load context + verify T111 complete">
      Confirm 111 ✅. Read T111 final code state (PlaybookTemplateContextBuilder, modified PlaybookOrchestrationService.ApplyConfigJsonTemplates, modified PromptSchemaRenderer.Render, modified AiCompletion + AiAnalysis). Read the spike design doc to recall design rationale.
    </step>
    <step order="2" name="Author SPAARKE-PLAYBOOK-LLM-OUTPUT-PATTERN.md (architecture doc)">
      Create `docs/architecture/SPAARKE-PLAYBOOK-LLM-OUTPUT-PATTERN.md`. Structure:
      - Title + purpose (one paragraph: what pattern, why it exists)
      - Two-layer architecture diagram + explanation
      - Layer 1 deep dive: PlaybookTemplateContextBuilder + ITemplateEngine + ApplyConfigJsonTemplates. Cite file paths + line numbers.
      - Layer 2 deep dive: PromptSchemaRenderer "## Input" section + AI executor inputBinding extraction. Cite file paths.
      - Runtime data flow: 6-step trace from playbook trigger through to LLM call (sequence diagram in markdown or ASCII art).
      - Component model: which files do what. Table format.
      - What's centralized vs what's per-consumer. Table format. Address operator's "scaling concern" explicitly.
      - When to use this pattern (vs hardcoded C# prompts, vs other AI dispatch). 1-2 paragraphs.
      - Cross-references: ADR-013, ADR-037, AI-ARCHITECTURE.md, ai-architecture-actions-nodes-scopes.md, JPS-AUTHORING-GUIDE.md.
      - Failure modes table (orphan placeholders, missing inputBinding, malformed JSON, etc.)
      Target: 300-400 lines.
    </step>
    <step order="3" name="Author BUILD-A-NEW-NARRATIVE-OUTPUT-CONSUMER.md (maker guide)">
      Create `docs/guides/BUILD-A-NEW-NARRATIVE-OUTPUT-CONSUMER.md`. Structure:
      - Title + audience (playbook + Action JPS authors; not devs)
      - Quick decision tree: when this pattern applies
      - Pre-flight checklist (Dataverse access, ITemplateEngine + AiCompletion executor available, etc.)
      - Step-by-step tutorial (each step = one authoring action):
        1. Decide what triggers the consumer
        2. Author the Action JPS (paste template; explain instruction.* fields; explain input.parameters declarative metadata)
        3. Compose the playbook (Start, intermediate nodes for data fetch, AiCompletion node with inputBinding, destination node)
        4. Author the output destination (UpdateRecord vs ReturnResponse vs SendEmail vs CreateNotification)
        5. Deploy (Action via Sync script or MCP, playbook via Deploy-Playbook.ps1)
        6. Test (curl /endpoint or trigger fire; inspect NodeOutput; inspect destination)
      - Worked example 1: Daily Briefing TL;DR (full source playbook + Action + screenshot of widget output)
      - Worked example 2: Insight Engine Matter Performance Summary (full pseudocode/design; no shipped impl yet — included as a future example to ground the pattern)
      - Common gotchas (template not resolving → check Layer 1 wiring, LLM doesn't see data → check inputBinding extraction, etc.)
      - Reference (links to architecture doc + ADRs + skill files)
      Target: 350-400 lines.
    </step>
    <step order="4" name="Update root CLAUDE.md §17 pointer table">
      Add new row to the pointer table for `docs/architecture/SPAARKE-PLAYBOOK-LLM-OUTPUT-PATTERN.md` with one-line description. Add row for `docs/guides/BUILD-A-NEW-NARRATIVE-OUTPUT-CONSUMER.md` if maker-guide section of pointer table exists. Position rows near existing AI-architecture pointers.
    </step>
    <step order="5" name="Cross-link from existing AI architecture docs">
      Add cross-reference lines to:
      - `docs/architecture/AI-ARCHITECTURE.md` (one paragraph + link in playbook section)
      - `docs/architecture/ai-architecture-actions-nodes-scopes.md` (one paragraph + link in Actions section)
      - `docs/architecture/ai-architecture-playbook-runtime.md` (one paragraph + link in runtime resolution section)
      - `docs/guides/JPS-AUTHORING-GUIDE.md` (one paragraph + link in narrative output section)
      Avoid creating SUPERSEDED markers — these are augmentations, not replacements.
    </step>
    <step order="6" name="Verify cross-references resolve + no broken links">
      Grep for any broken file references in the new docs. Verify cross-links go both ways (existing docs → new pattern doc; new pattern doc → existing docs). Confirm root CLAUDE.md §17 row visible.
    </step>
    <step order="7" name="Update TASK-INDEX + current-task.md">
      Mark 111a ✅; advance current-task.md to T112 (next pending task).
    </step>
    <step order="8" name="Commit">
      Single commit. Body documents: new pattern doc + maker guide + cross-link updates. Reference operator binding 2026-06-29.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>Read (existing docs + T111 implementation files)</tool>
    <tool>Write (2 new docs)</tool>
    <tool>Edit (CLAUDE.md + 4 existing AI architecture docs for cross-links)</tool>
